The method was added in #17721. Right now it is not used in production code (as far as I can tell, never was used there), it is used only in tests, in `src\ExpressionEvaluator\CSharp\Test\ExpressionCompiler\CompileExpressionsTests.cs`. It looks like all tests, but one were added in the same PR that added the method. The one test added later compiles a single expression. 

It is not clear what was the intent for the method. Since it resides in production code, its behavior should be tested, which increases our test matrix. For example, if we are changing some of the methods used by `CompileExpressions` to take a new input in order to behave properly in certain scenarios, we should test that `CompileExpressions` provides correct input, etc. However, if the method is meant to be a test helper and is not meant to be used in production code, then testing it would not be a smart way to spend dev resources.

We should consider moving `CompileExpressions` out of the production code and to location where other EE test helpers reside. It might be simpler and better to remove it completely. Currently only 12 tests are using it and 6 of them pass a single expression. It could be fairly simple to switch the tests to use `CompileExpression` API instead.

## Background and Motivation

Some analyzers provide diagnostics and code fixes for embedded languages. A example of an embedded language would be SQL syntax inside a C# string, which is a common practice for business applications. An analyzer might be built to error on invalid T-SQL syntax or to suggest best practices such as requiring columns to be qualified.

The source location for such diagnostics should be the relevant _subset_ of the string literal token. For example:

```cs
var widgets = await connection.QueryAsync<Widget>("""
    select Widgets.Id, Parts.Id, {|XYZ0001:Name|}
    from dbo.Widgets
    join dbo.Parts on Parts.WidgetId = Widgets.Id
    """);
```

Where `{|XYZ0001:Name|}` signifies that the embedded text `Name` should be the location of a diagnostic XYZ0001.

In order to report a diagnostic, the analyzer must translate from _embedded_ string offsets within the unescaped string value (such as from `ILiteralOperation.ConstantValue`) to _source offsets_ within the C# file.

This translation currently requires the analyzer to understand and translate all escapes, as well as trimming raw string indentation _properly_. If `\u2014` appears in the C# string, the embedded language within the string does not receive a backslash, a lowercase U, and some hex digits; instead, the embedded language gains a single em dash character in this case. This is not solved once and done; C# recently added a new escape sequence, `\e`. C# also recently added raw string literals, and the analyzer is required to understand the intervening trimmed indentation.

Such a mapping from embedded language offsets to source file offsets is highly nuanced. It is a large burden for analyzers to solve this from scratch each time, and analyzers cannot remain language-agnostic while doing so.

Further, if the code fix wants to modify the string literal, it will not only need to know the source file offsets that match the embedded construct, it will also need to know how to escape characters. Any embedded language character that it may be inserting may need escaping in order to appear within the C# string.

## Proposed API

Two things have thus far been identified as lacking:
- A language-agnostic API to map from a given ILiteralOperation or SyntaxToken, plus a given offset into the unescaped embedded string value, to a location in the containing source file.
- A language-agnostic API to escape character values for inclusion in literal strings.

It could be a good idea to tie together the consumption of the unescaped characters with the source file span for each character. This would improve the API usability since you would no longer have to "just know" that you use GetOperation + ILiteralOperation.ConstantValue to get the unescaped string, and then get a service from some other place to map its internal offsets back to the file. Also, could there be a performance advantage in analyzing a SyntaxToken directly rather than going through IOperation to get it?

Roslyn has already solved cleanly with its internal [`IVirtualCharService`](https://sourceroslyn.io/#Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.Workspaces/IVirtualCharService.cs). `IVirtualCharService` powers Roslyn's own embedded language support for JSON, regular expressions, and others. The interface has stood the test of time. The existence of `Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.ExternalAccess.AspNetCore.EmbeddedLanguages.AspNetCoreCSharpVirtualCharService`, which is a copy of this API, also shows its usefulness.

Besides these goals, it may also be worth checking with what Roslyn has learned in the implementation of its own embedded language support, which has shaped `IVirtualCharService`. There may be more concerns that are relevant to analyzers that could be uncovered by doing so.

The proposed API is similar to IVirtualCharService, but it becomes a class instead of an interface so that new APIs can be added later.

```diff
+namespace Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.EmbeddedLanguages.VirtualChars
+{
+    public abstract class VirtualCharService
+    {
+        public static VirtualCharService GetVirtualCharService(SyntaxTree tree);
+
+        public virtual VirtualCharSequence TryConvertToVirtualChars(SyntaxToken token, CancellationToken cancellationToken);
+        public virtual bool TryGetEscapeCharacter(VirtualChar virtualChar, out char escapeChar);
+    }
+
+    public readonly struct VirtualCharSequence
+    {
+        public bool IsDefault { get; }
+        public int Length { get; }
+        public VirtualChar this[int index] { get; }
+
+        // New functionality
+        public VirtualChar GetVirtualCharAtUtf16Index(int index);
+
+        public override string ToString();
+        public Enumerator GetEnumerator();
+
+        public struct Enumerator : IEnumerator<VirtualChar>
+        {
+            public bool MoveNext();
+            public readonly VirtualChar Current { get; }
+        }
+    }
+
+    public readonly struct VirtualChar : IEquatable<VirtualChar>, IEquatable<char>, IComparable<VirtualChar>, IComparable<char>
+    {
+        /// <summary>
+        /// The value of this <see cref="VirtualChar"/> as a <see cref="Rune"/> if such a representation is possible.
+        /// <see cref="Rune"/>s can represent Unicode codepoints that can appear in a <see cref="string"/> except for
+        /// unpaired surrogates.  If an unpaired high or low surrogate character is present, this value will be <see
+        /// cref="Rune.ReplacementChar"/>.  The value of this character can be retrieved from
+        /// <see cref="SurrogateChar"/>.
+        /// </summary>
+        public readonly Rune Rune { get; }
+ 
+        /// <summary>
+        /// The unpaired high or low surrogate character that was encountered that could not be represented in <see
+        /// cref="Rune"/>.  If <see cref="Rune"/> is not <see cref="Rune.ReplacementChar"/>, this will be <c>0</c>.
+        /// </summary>
+        public readonly char SurrogateChar { get; }
+ 
+        /// <summary>
+        /// The span of characters in the original <see cref="SourceText"/> that represent this <see
+        /// cref="VirtualChar"/>.
+        /// </summary>
+        public readonly TextSpan Span { get; }
+
+        public override string ToString();
+        public void AppendTo(StringBuilder builder);
+
+        public override int GetHashCode();
+        public override bool Equals(object? obj);
+        public bool Equals(VirtualChar other);
+        public static bool operator ==(VirtualChar left, VirtualChar right);
+        public static bool operator !=(VirtualChar left, VirtualChar right);
+
+        public bool Equals(char other);
+        public static bool operator ==(VirtualChar left, char right);
+        public static bool operator !=(VirtualChar left, char right);
+
+        public int CompareTo(VirtualChar other);
+        public static bool operator <(VirtualChar left, VirtualChar right);
+        public static bool operator <=(VirtualChar left, VirtualChar right);
+        public static bool operator >(VirtualChar left, VirtualChar right);
+        public static bool operator >=(VirtualChar left, VirtualChar right);
+
+        public int CompareTo(char other);
+        public static bool operator <(VirtualChar left, char right);
+        public static bool operator <=(VirtualChar left, char right);
+        public static bool operator >(VirtualChar left, char right);
+        public static bool operator >=(VirtualChar left, char right);
+    }
+
+    public readonly struct Rune : IComparable<Rune>, IEquatable<Rune>
+    {
+       // [Copied from System.Text.Rune]
+    }
+}
```

It may be worth exposing more members on these types as well, such as the LINQ-style instance methods on VirtualCharSequence.

Code fixes which work with embedded languages may find themselves needing a helper to replace virtual chars inside a token. When this happens across multiple lines, and the token is a raw string literal, this becomes much more complex than simply escaping the virtual characters and replacing the source text span from the start to the end. A raw string literal's trimmed indentation intervenes. Contiguous _virtual_ chars may map to noncontiguous source spans. Something will need to detect the indentation for the raw string and insert it at every inserted newline. This may be a job for a different API in the workspaces layer.

## Usage Examples

```c#
var literalOperation = (ILiteralOperation)context.Operation;

VirtualCharService virtualCharService = VirtualCharService.GetVirtualCharService(literalOperation.Syntax.SyntaxTree);
VirtualCharSequence virtualCharSequence = virtualCharService.TryConvertToVirtualChars(literalOperation.Syntax, context.CancellationToken);
if (virtualCharSequence.IsDefault)
    return;

using var textReader = new StringReader(virtualCharSequence.ToString());
StatementList statementList = TSqlParser.ParseStatementList(textReader, out var parseErrors);

foreach (ParseError error in parseErrors)
{
    VirtualChar virtualChar = virtualCharSequence.GetVirtualCharAtUtf16Index(error.Offset);
    int sourceStart = virtualChar.Span.Start;

    // The TSQL parser doesn't give lengths with the errors, so make the diagnostic as long as the single T-SQL
    // token at the error position. (TODO: Optimize the lookup)
    TSqlParserToken? nextToken = statementList.ScriptTokenStream.FirstOrDefault(token => token.Offset > error.Offset);
    int sourceEnd = nextToken is null
        ? virtualCharSequence[^1].Span.End
        : virtualCharSequence.GetVirtualCharAtUtf16Index(nextToken.Offset).Span.Start;

    context.ReportDiagnostic(Diagnostic.Create(
        DiagnosticDescriptors.InvalidTSqlSyntax,
        Location.Create(literalOperation.Syntax.SyntaxTree, TextSpan.FromBounds(sourceStart, sourceEnd)),
        [error.Message, error.Number]));
}

// Use visitor pattern to continue analyzing 'statementList', using TSqlParserToken offsets within
```

## Alternative Designs

Instead of iterating runes, the design could iterate chars. This comes with a potential hit to usability. An analyzer that finds a surrogate pair may want to know what the pair represents. In order to know that, the analyzer can no longer walk over the characters using one iteration of the enumerator at a time.

Instead of shipping a Roslyn-specific Rune class, a new Microsoft.Bcl.Rune package could be created so that .NET Standard analyzers can access System.Text.Rune. Roslyn already depends on one of the Microsoft.Bcl packages, Microsoft.Bcl.AsyncInterfaces.

## Risks

If Roslyn's own battle-tested `IVirtualCharService` implementation is made public, there will be no immediate risk, but having the interface and associated types public may constrain future iterations as always.

